Because squash has unsuccessfully lobbied for decades to be included at the Olympics, it is very easy to think Martin is just being bitter. But none other than World Athletics President Sebastian Coe cried foul after cross country failed to make it into the programme for 2024 Olympic Games.
In Coe’s view, cross country is an exciting and fast growing sport around the world which deserved a place at the Olympics, given its heritage in France at the 1924 Paris Olympics.
I was also taken aback by the admission of breakdancing to the Olympics. It does not help things that it has come at the expense of cross country, a competition in which Kenya has a good track. The legendary Paul Tergat and John Ngugi each won a record five world cross country titles, and Hellen Obiri currently holds the women’s world title.
The changes are part of Olympic Agenda 2020, a set of 40 recommendations adopted by the IOC session in 2014. According to IOC, the changes are aimed at safeguarding the Olympic values and strengthening the role of sport in society. They were driven by a recognition that the world was evolving rapidly and that the Olympic Movement had the opportunity to be an agent of change.





My take is that the changes are well-intended, but the classification and implementation is wanting. Rather than make breakdancing an Olympic sport, it can allow breakdancing championships to run parallel to the Olympic Games as it did with wushu tournament in 2008 in Beijing.



